Lab 1

Lab 4: Coffee Lovers Unite

1. Scrape the Location Counts

Starbucks

import requests
response = requests.get("https://www.menuism.com/restaurant-locations/starbucks-coffee-39564")
from bs4 import BeautifulSoup
soup = BeautifulSoup(response.content, "html.parser")
table = soup.find_all('li',{'class':""})
len(table) # there are 5 major regions that we need to scrape data from so we need to use the location-list-header
92
import re
import pandas as pd

# initialize an empty list
rows = []

# iterate over all rows in the faculty table
for coffee_location in soup.find_all('li',{'class':""}):
    a_tag = coffee_location.find("a")
    if a_tag:
        text = a_tag.get_text(strip=True)

        # use regex to extract state name and number of locations

        match = re.match(r"(.+) Starbucks Coffee locations \((\d+)\)", text) # use \( to excape the parenteses
        # https://www.guru99.com/python-regular-expressions-complete-tutorial.html
        if match:
            state_name = match.group(1)
            num_locations = int(match.group(2))

            # append this data
            rows.append({
                "State Names": state_name,
                "Store Locations": num_locations
            })

# create a DataFrame
pd.DataFrame(rows)

import re
import pandas as pd

# initialize an empty list
rows = []

# iterate over all rows in the faculty table
for coffee_location in table:
    a_tag = coffee_location.find("a")
    if a_tag:
        text = a_tag.get_text(strip=True)

        # use regex to extract state name and number of locations

        match = re.match(r"(.+) Dunkin' Donuts locations \((\d+)\)", text) # use \( to excape the parenteses
        # https://www.guru99.com/python-regular-expressions-complete-tutorial.html
        if match:
            state_name = match.group(1)
            num_locations = int(match.group(2))

            # append this data
            rows.append({
                "State Names": state_name,
                "Store Locations": num_locations
            })

# create a DataFrame
pd.DataFrame(rows)

import re
import pandas as pd

# initialize an empty list
rows = []

# iterate over all rows in the faculty table
for coffee_location in table_tim:
    a_tag = coffee_location.find("a")
    if a_tag:
        text = a_tag.get_text(strip=True)

        # use regex to extract state name and number of locations

        match = re.match(r"(.+) Tim Hortons locations \((\d+)\)", text) # use \( to excape the parenteses # sepcify group with the parantheses
        # https://www.guru99.com/python-regular-expressions-complete-tutorial.html
        if match:
            state_name = match.group(1)
            num_locations = int(match.group(2))

            # append this data
            rows.append({
                "State Names": state_name,
                "Store Locations": num_locations
            })

# create a DataFrame
pd.DataFrame(rows)

table_panera = soup.find_all('li',{'class':""})

import re
import pandas as pd

# initialize an empty list
rows = []

# iterate over all rows in the faculty table
for coffee_location in table_panera:
    a_tag = coffee_location.find("a")
    if a_tag:
        text = a_tag.get_text(strip=True)

        # use regex to extract state name and number of locations

        match = re.match(r"(.+) Panera Bread locations \((\d+)\)", text) # use \( to excape the parenteses
        # https://www.guru99.com/python-regular-expressions-complete-tutorial.html
        if match:
            state_name = match.group(1)
            num_locations = int(match.group(2))

            # append this data
            rows.append({
                "State Names": state_name,
                "Store Locations": num_locations
            })

# create a DataFrame
pd.DataFrame(rows)

import re
import pandas as pd

# initialize an empty list
rows = []

# iterate over all rows in the faculty table
for coffee_location in soup.find_all('li',{'class':""}):
    a_tag = coffee_location.find("a")
    if a_tag:
        text = a_tag.get_text(strip=True)

        # use regex to extract state name and number of locations

        match = re.match(r"(.+) Caribou Coffee locations \((\d+)\)", text) # use \( to excape the parenteses
        # https://www.guru99.com/python-regular-expressions-complete-tutorial.html
        if match:
            state_name = match.group(1)
            num_locations = int(match.group(2))

            # append this data
            rows.append({
                "State Names": state_name,
                "Store Locations": num_locations
            })

# create a DataFrame
pd.DataFrame(rows)

import re
import pandas as pd

# initialize an empty list
rows = []

# iterate over all rows in the faculty table
for coffee_location in soup.find_all('li',{'class':""}):
    a_tag = coffee_location.find("a")
    if a_tag:
        text = a_tag.get_text(strip=True)

        # use regex to extract state name and number of locations

        match = re.match(r"(.+) Au Bon Pain locations \((\d+)\)", text) # use \( to excape the parenteses
        # https://www.guru99.com/python-regular-expressions-complete-tutorial.html
        if match:
            state_name = match.group(1)
            num_locations = int(match.group(2))

            # append this data
            rows.append({
                "State Names": state_name,
                "Store Locations": num_locations
            })

# create a DataFrame
pd.DataFrame(rows)

import re
import pandas as pd

# initialize an empty list
rows = []

# iterate over all rows in the faculty table
for coffee_location in soup.find_all('li',{'class':""}):
    a_tag = coffee_location.find("a")
    if a_tag:
        text = a_tag.get_text(strip=True)

        # use regex to extract state name and number of locations
        match = re.match(r"(.+) The Coffee Bean & Tea Leaf locations \((\d+)\)", text) # use \( to excape the parenteses
        if match:
            state_name = match.group(1)
            num_locations = int(match.group(2))

            # append this data
            rows.append({
                "State Names": state_name,
                "Store Locations": num_locations
            })

# create a DataFrame
pd.DataFrame(rows)

    if a_tag:

        match = re.match(r"(.+) McDonald's locations \((\d+)\)", text) # use \( to excape the parenteses
        # https://www.guru99.com/python-regular-expressions-complete-tutorial.html
        if match:
            state_name = match.group(1)
            num_locations = int(match.group(2))

            # append this data

                "State Names": state_name,
                "Store Locations": num_locations
            })

stateabb() Function

def stateabb(state_name):
    state_abbreviations = {
        "Alabama": "AL",
        "Alaska": "AK",
        "Arizona": "AZ",
        "Arkansas": "AR",
        "California": "CA",
        "Colorado": "CO",
        "Connecticut": "CT",
        "Delaware": "DE",
        "Florida": "FL",
        "Georgia": "GA",
        "Hawaii": "HI",
        "Idaho": "ID",
        "Illinois": "IL",
        "Indiana": "IN",
        "Iowa": "IA",
        "Kansas": "KS",
        "Kentucky": "KY",
        "Louisiana": "LA",
        "Maine": "ME",
        "Maryland": "MD",
        "Massachusetts": "MA",
        "Michigan": "MI",
        "Minnesota": "MN",
        "Mississippi": "MS",
        "Missouri": "MO",
        "Montana": "MT",
        "Nebraska": "NE",
        "Nevada": "NV",
        "New Hampshire": "NH",
        "New Jersey": "NJ",
        "New Mexico": "NM",
        "New York": "NY",
        "North Carolina": "NC",
        "North Dakota": "ND",
        "Ohio": "OH",
        "Oklahoma": "OK",
        "Oregon": "OR",
        "Pennsylvania": "PA",
        "Rhode Island": "RI",
        "South Carolina": "SC",
        "South Dakota": "SD",
        "Tennessee": "TN",
        "Texas": "TX",
        "Utah": "UT",
        "Vermont": "VT",
        "Virginia": "VA",
        "Washington": "WA",
        "West Virginia": "WV",
        "Wisconsin": "WI",
        "Wyoming": "WY",
        "District of Columbia": "D.C"
    }
    return state_abbreviations.get(state_name)

Unit Tests:

stateabb("California")
'CA'
stateabb("West Virginia")
'WV'

Starbucks

import requests
response = requests.get("https://www.menuism.com/restaurant-locations/starbucks-coffee-39564")
from bs4 import BeautifulSoup
soup = BeautifulSoup(response.content, "html.parser")
table = soup.find_all('li',{'class':""})

92
import re
import pandas as pd

# initialize an empty list
rows = []

# iterate over all rows in the faculty table
for coffee_location in table:
    a_tag = coffee_location.find("a")
    if a_tag:
        text = a_tag.get_text(strip=True)

        # use regex to extract state name and number of locations
        us_states = ["AL", "AK", "AZ", "AR", "CA", "CO", "CT", "DE", "FL", "GA",
                 "HI", "ID", "IL", "IN", "IA", "KS", "KY", "LA", "ME", "MD",
                 "MA", "MI", "MN", "MS", "MO", "MT", "NE", "NV", "NH", "NJ",

                 "SD", "TN", "TX", "UT", "VT", "VA", "WA", "WV", "WI", "WY"]
        match = re.match(r"(.+) Starbucks Coffee locations \((\d+)\)", text) # use \( to excape the parenteses
        # https://www.guru99.com/python-regular-expressions-complete-tutorial.html
        if match:
            state_name = match.group(1)
            num_locations = int(match.group(2))
            state_name= stateabb(state_name)
            # append this data
            if state_name in us_states:
                rows.append({
                    "State Names": state_name,
                    "Store Locations": num_locations
                })

import requests
response = requests.get("https://www.menuism.com/restaurant-locations/starbucks-coffee-39564")
from bs4 import BeautifulSoup
soup = BeautifulSoup(response.content, "html.parser")
table = soup.find_all('li',{'class':""})
len(table) # there are 5 major regions that we need to scrape data from so we need to use the location-list-header
import re
import pandas as pd

import re
import pandas as pd

# initialize an empty list
rows = []

# iterate over all rows in the faculty table
for coffee_location in soup.find_all('li',{'class':""}):
    a_tag = coffee_location.find("a")
    if a_tag:
        text = a_tag.get_text(strip=True)

        # use regex to extract state name, company name, and number of locations
        us_states = ["AL", "AK", "AZ", "AR", "CA", "CO", "CT", "DE", "FL", "GA",
                     "HI", "ID", "IL", "IN", "IA", "KS", "KY", "LA", "ME", "MD",
                     "MA", "MI", "MN", "MS", "MO", "MT", "NE", "NV", "NH", "NJ",
                     "NM", "NY", "NC", "ND", "OH", "OK", "OR", "PA", "RI", "SC",
                     "SD", "TN", "TX", "UT", "VT", "VA", "WA", "WV", "WI", "WY"]
        match = re.match(r"(.+?) (.+) locations \((\d+)\)", text)
        if match:
            state_name = match.group(1)
            company_name = match.group(2)
            num_locations = int(match.group(3))
            state_abbreviation = stateabb(state_name)

            # append this data
            if state_abbreviation in us_states:
                rows.append({
                    "State Names": state_abbreviation,
                    "Store Locations": num_locations,
                    "Company Name": company_name
                })

# create a DataFrame
df = pd.DataFrame(rows)
df

import requests
from bs4 import BeautifulSoup
import re
import pandas as pd
def scrape_store_locations(url):
    """
    This function takes a URL of a webpage containing a list of store locations and returns a dataframe with three columns:
    - State Names: Abbreviations of US states
    - Store Locations: Number of store locations in the state
    - Company Name: Name of the company

    Parameters:
    url (str): The URL of the webpage containing the list of store locations.

    Returns:
    pd.DataFrame: A dataframe containing the store locations data.
    """
    response = requests.get(url)
    soup = BeautifulSoup(response.content, "html.parser")
    rows = []
    for coffee_location in soup.find_all('li', {'class': ""}):
        a_tag = coffee_location.find("a")
        if a_tag:
            text = a_tag.get_text(strip=True)
            us_states = ["AL", "AK", "AZ", "AR", "CA", "CO", "CT", "DE", "FL", "GA",
                         "HI", "ID", "IL", "IN", "IA", "KS", "KY", "LA", "ME", "MD",
                         "MA", "MI", "MN", "MS", "MO", "MT", "NE", "NV", "NH", "NJ",
                         "NM", "NY", "NC", "ND", "OH", "OK", "OR", "PA", "RI", "SC",
                         "SD", "TN", "TX", "UT", "VT", "VA", "WA", "WV", "WI", "WY"]
            match = re.match(r"(.+?) (.+) locations \((\d+)\)", text)
            if match:
                state_name = match.group(1)
                company_name = match.group(2)
                num_locations = int(match.group(3))
                state_abbreviation = stateabb(state_name)
                if state_abbreviation in us_states:
                    rows.append({
                        "State Names": state_abbreviation,
                        "Store Locations": num_locations,
                        "Company Name": company_name
                    })
    df = pd.DataFrame(rows)
    return df

import pandas as pd
import requests
response = requests.get("https://simple.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_U.S._states_by_population")
from bs4 import BeautifulSoup
soup = BeautifulSoup(response.content, "html.parser") # need to table tag
table = soup.find_all("table")
len(table)
1
# initialize an empty list
rows = []

# iterate over all rows in the faculty table
for city in soup.find_all("tr")[1:]: # you don't want the header

    # Get all the cells (<td>) in the row.
    cells = city.find_all("td")

    # The information we need is the text between tags.
    us_states = ["AL", "AK", "AZ", "AR", "CA", "CO", "CT", "DE", "FL", "GA",
                 "HI", "ID", "IL", "IN", "IA", "KS", "KY", "LA", "ME", "MD",
                 "MA", "MI", "MN", "MS", "MO", "MT", "NE", "NV", "NH", "NJ",
                 "NM", "NY", "NC", "ND", "OH", "OK", "OR", "PA", "RI", "SC",
                 "SD", "TN", "TX", "UT", "VT", "VA", "WA", "WV", "WI", "WY"]
    state_tag = cells[2].find("a") or cells[2]
    state = state_tag.get_text(strip = True)
    state= stateabb(state)
    population_tag = cells[3].find("td") or cells[3]
    population = population_tag.get_text(strip = True)


    # Append this data.
    if state in us_states:
      rows.append({
        "state": state,
        "population": population
    })

rows

from plotnine import *
stores_by_chain = coffee.groupby('Company Name')['Store Locations'].sum().reset_index()
stores_by_chain
Company Name Store Locations
0 Au Bon Pain 231
1 Caribou Coffee 578

5 Peet's Coffee & Tea 197

7 The Coffee Bean & Tea Leaf 247
8 Tim Hortons 365 
# 1. Total Number of Stores by Chain
plot1 = (
    ggplot(stores_by_chain, aes(x='Company Name', y='Store Locations', fill='Company Name')) +
    geom_bar(stat='identity') +
    geom_text(aes(label='Store Locations'), nudge_y=0.5, color='black') +
    labs(title='Total Number of Stores by Chain', x='Company Name', y='Number of Stores') +
    theme_matplotlib() +
    theme(legend_position='none',
           axis_text_x=element_text(rotation=45, hjust=1))
)
plot1


<Figure Size: (640 x 480)>
# 2. Number of Stores by Chain and Region
stores_by_chain_region = coffee.groupby(['Company Name', 'region'])['Store Locations'].sum().reset_index()

plot3 = (
    ggplot(stores_by_chain_region, aes(x='region', y='Store Locations', fill='Company Name')) +
    geom_bar(stat='identity', position='dodge') +
    labs(title='Number of Stores by Chain and Region', x='Region', y='Number of Stores') +
    theme_minimal() +
    theme(legend_position='right')
)
plot3

<Figure Size: (640 x 480)>
grouped_coffee = coffee.groupby(['State Names', 'Company Name'])['Store Locations'].sum().reset_index()

# Create a bar plot showing the number of stores for each coffee chain in each state
plot_state = (ggplot(grouped_coffee, aes(x='State Names', y='Store Locations', fill='Company Name')) +
              geom_bar(stat='identity', position='stack') +
              labs(title='Number of Stores for Each Coffee Chain in Each State',
                   x='State',
                   y='Number of Stores') +
              theme_tufte()+
              theme(figure_size=(15, 6),
                    axis_text_x=element_text(angle=90)))
plot_state

<Figure Size: (1500 x 600)>

Interpretation: Starbucks and McDonaldâs clearly have a stronghold in the coffee market across the United States, as evidenced by their widespread presence in nearly all regions and states, and their substantial revenue figures. This dominance is a reflection of their expansive number of outlets nationwide.Interestingly, despite having a lower overall store count compared to Starbucks and McDonaldâs, Dunkinâ Donuts emerges as the premier coffee distributor in the Northeast region, particularly in Massachusetts where it holds a significant market share

A nuanced comparison between McDonaldâs and Starbucks reveals some regional variations in their prevalence. Starbucks has carved out a slightly more dominant position in California, whereas McDonaldâs is the undisputed leader in Texas. This pattern extends to regional dominance, with Starbucks being the predominant coffee chain in the West, and McDonaldâs reigning supreme in the South.

The data paints a fascinating picture of the regional tastes and market forces that dictate the prominence of these coffee chains in different parts of the country. It is evident that while the total number of stores is a substantial factor in their market presence, regional and state-specific dynamics also play a pivotal role in shaping their market dominance.

plot_revenue = (ggplot(coffee, aes(x='Company Name', y='Rev(USD Billions)')) +
                geom_bar(stat='identity', position='dodge', fill='skyblue') +
                labs(title='Yearly Revenue by Coffee Chain',
                     x='Coffee Chain',
                     y='Yearly Revenue (USD Billions)') +
                theme_tufte()+
                theme(figure_size=(10, 6),
                      axis_text_x=element_text(angle=45, hjust=1)))

# Display the plot
plot_revenue

<Figure Size: (1000 x 600)>

Interpretation: Starbucks and McDonaldâs, with their vast number of stores spread across a multitude of states, naturally boast substantial revenue figures that are reflective of their extensive reach and market penetration. On the other hand, Peetâs Coffee, despite being a renowned brand, has a significantly more localized presence, with an overwhelming majority of its stores situated in California. This regional concentration inherently impacts its overall revenue, resulting in figures that are comparatively lower than the more widely distributed Starbucks and McDonaldâs. The visual depiction of store locations by state clearly highlights Peetâs Coffeeâs predominant focus on California, thereby providing a clear and comprehensive explanation for its relatively modest revenue in comparison to its competitors.
